\fs28 \cf2 \cb3 Thank you. Well, now with this broad, comprehensive picture that Simon has given and also the other presentations, I will move to the more general stage to focus on what tools will be needed to produce regulatory research that is faster and more reliable.\cb1 \
\cb3 So at this stage, the key issue is not only whether AI can help us to find legal information, but the more relevant question is whether the tool can transform that information into regulatory evidence. With this, I mean a documented record linking the regulatory measure.\cb1 \
\cb3 to its legal source, provision of text, translation, timeline, and the methodological relevance.\cb1 \
\cb3 If so, this regulatory evidence needs to be structured, comparable, and auditable. Otherwise, the tool may save the time at the search stage, but can create new problems at the review stage.\cb1 \
\cb3 In practical terms, the output must be aligned with the methodology followed. And for our case, this should, among other things, identify the country, the relevant pillars and indicators, the legal instrument, specific provisions, dates, among other things.\cb1 \
\cb3 So to ensure that an AI tool is useful for comparative regulatory research, I will focus on three essential elements, format, citation quality, and language coverage.\cb1 \
\cb3 The first element is format. So, once the tool finds a relevant law or regulation, how should it present that information so that the researcher can verify and use it in a proper way?\cb1 \
\cb3 Among the most informative, information must be structured, must be machine readable and compatible with the software you are using for your research. In this sense, for the database like the DTI, a paragraph level answer is not enough.\cb1 \
\cb3 The tool should produce outputs that can be directly reviewed and compared by the researchers.\cb1 \
\cb3 And with these outputs that can be directly reviewed and compared, I mean that findings should be broken down in different fields. For example, in the case of the DTI or the Regional Data Trade Integration Index, the tool should separately identify the country, the relevant pillar indicator.\cb1 \
\cb3 Provisions, as I mentioned, the source, date, and likewise, it should include flags of uncertainty, missing information, contradictory sources, and possible amendments and repeals of the different laws and regulations.\cb1 \
\cb3 This matters because comparability, it depends on the structure. If two researchers receive unstructured summaries, they may code similar measures differently, but if they receive the same type of evidence in the same type of format.\cb1 \
\cb3 the review can become faster and more consistent. Yes, 3 min. Thank you.\cb1 \
\cb3 Next slide, please.\cb1 \
\cb3 So the second element is citation quality. When we get a structured output, how do we ensure that this one is auditable for researchers and for the general public?\cb1 \
\cb3 In regulatory analysis, a generic citation to a law is rarely sufficient. If the tool says that the country has a data localization requirement, for example, we need to know exactly where the requirement is located.\cb1 \
\cb3 Is this in a statute, in an implementing regulation, in a decree, or is in a specific sector guideline? This is particularly relevant because secondary sources, as mentioned, Simon, may refer to a legislation.\cb1 \
\cb3 Sometimes the specific provisions, the dates of which these measures apply are not included. As well, when using primary sources, they may contradict, complement, or modify each other. A law may establish a general rule, while a decree, guideline, or sector regulation may define the actual compliance obligation.\cb1 \
\cb3 For this reason, the tool should not only cite the document, but also identify the exact article, section, or paragraph.\cb1 \
\cb3 with the enforcement states and amendments.\cb1 \
\cb3 Good citation quality is what makes the output auditable. The researcher should be able to move from the proposed classification back to the original legal source quickly and transparently.\cb1 \
\cb3 The third requirement is language coverage. Please, next slide.\cb1 \
\cb3 Although many countries have a.\cb1 \
\cb3 Next slide, please.\cb1 \
\cb3 Although many countries have adequate translations of their laws, many of the most relevant legal sources are not available in English, in countries where English is not their first language. Therefore, if a tool relies primarily on English language sources, it will replicate existing coverage gaps and may overlook.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

