\fs28 \cf2 \cb3 Precisely those countries where support is most needed.\cb1 \
\cb3 However, this does not mean that researchers should rely only on tools given by AI translation. Ideally, the tool should provide a reliable translation, but also retain the original legal text.\cb1 \
\cb3 and indicate the relevant provision in both documents. This is important because legal meaning often depends on specific terms, institutional reference or drafting conventions, and in this regard it is essential to verify and compare the provisions of the translation.\cb1 \
\cb3 in both of the texts, the translation and the original one. Ideally, the tool should also flag uncertainty, and for example, if a term has not.\cb1 \
\cb3 clear legal equivalent in English, or if the translation depends on a context, this should be visible for the reviewer.\cb1 \
\cb3 And finally.\cb1 \
\cb3 Next slide, please. Once the tool has been has produced those output.\cb1 \
\cb3 How should the researcher use them? AI can accelerate the preparation stage of regulatory research, but final verification, interpretation, and coding must remain with the human researchers.\cb1 \
\cb3 In comparative regulatory work, the most difficult part is often not finding a document, but deciding how this document fits in the methodology. For this reason, the strongest contribution of AI would be to reduce the time spent on discovery, extraction, and citation.\cb1 \
\cb3 while keeping human researchers responsible for the final validation.\cb1 \
\cb3 Thank you very much.\cb1 \
