\fs28 \cf2 \cb3 In every AI system, you need to have multiple iterations. You cannot expect the first version to be perfect. So your first version will just be okay.\cb1 \
\cb3 And then you continue to improve from your first version. And in order to do that.\cb1 \
\cb3 You need to identify first that what goods look like. Where do you want to go? Where do you need to be? What accuracy level that you need to match? What does it mean match?\cb1 \
\cb3 What does it mean good? How do you define good? I think that's the core. Because once you define what good looks like, then you can build the first version. Then you take feedback and iterate and reiterate toward the North Star of the project.\cb1 \
\cb3 So do not start a project without a clear definition of what goods looks like. So that's my first lesson learned, first principle.\cb1 \
\cb3 The second principle is, once you define what goods look like, and you understand the nature of AI project, where you need to build multiple iterations towards what goods look like.\cb1 \
\cb3 You need to build observability early in the game, meaning that you need to have telemetry monitoring, you need to have intermediate result monitoring, you need to have version control, you need to have arrival.\cb1 \
\cb3 unlock. You need to have a lock file. Anything that you can capture as a telemetry of each run will help you iterate much faster.\cb1 \
\cb3 In normal AI project, I have never seen any\'85\cb1 \
\cb3 good AI project that finished less than 3 iterations. So think about it, if you need to run this AI project at least 3 times, do you have enough luck, uh, to improve it on the second and the third iteration or not?\cb1 \
\cb3 And in order to have a good enough locks and telemetry, you need to design the observability very early in the game as well. That would be my recommendation.\cb1 \
\cb3 Uh, the third one is, uh, domain-bounded reasoning. I think I\'85 I've been listening to my\'85 all of my previous, uh, presenters, and I'm very enjoying.\cb1 \
\cb3 I guess what I'm trying to say is for those of you who are AI engineer, you absolutely cannot work in a legal and regulation domain without a very close collaboration with the legal and the regulatory expert.\cb1 \
\cb3 Uh, for example.\cb1 \
\cb3 Is data storage the same as.\cb1 \
\cb3 data processing from a legal standpoint no right but how do you define that in your prompts how do you teach your AI to distinguish the differences when it comes to not just a word but the interpretation of the word or another example is.\cb1 \
\cb3 If there's a regulation where you mandate a company to have a local registration in the country.\cb1 \
\cb3 Does it mean a national discrimination?\cb1 \
\cb3 I don't know. And if you don't tell AI, the AI will make its own assumption.\cb1 \
\cb3 So you need to collaborate and work very closely on the definition of.\cb1 \
\cb3 this is what it is this is not what it is with your legal expert in order to teach the AI with the right mindset or the right lens.\cb1 \
\cb3 I mentioned this already that eventually you need to have a very clear boundary between AI and code.\cb1 \
\cb3 The LLM is very good on semantic meaning, addressing ambiguity, reading human language, performing comparison, etc.\cb1 \
\cb3 But when it comes to validation, counting numbers, checking if the field is corrected, performing version control, scoring something, package the output in a structured way, I always use code, not using AI, because I need consistency.\cb1 \
\cb3 So, in the end, it's up to you, how do you define, this is what we need consistency, and this is where we need, you know, all the, uh, uh, uh, uh, nuances approach.\cb1 \
\cb3 Lastly, when you design this system, you heard from my earlier presenters as well, that we're not talking about one country, we're talking about multiple countries. And when\'85 and we talk about not just one domain, but multiple domains as well.\cb1 \
\cb3 So you're going to need to design.\cb1 \
\cb3 where\'85\cb1 \
\cb3 where the system should be generic, and where the system should be specific.\cb1 \
\cb3 If you design the system to be too generic, you will not be able to handle many things that are specific to that domain. On the other hand, if you design everything so specific, you can't scale out, you can't like\'85\cb1 \
\cb3 Hey, I build this for Thailand law, for Thailand law, and you want to replicate this same methodology to address Malaysia law. If you make it too specific, you won't be able to do that. So you need to, you know, design your system. Again, it's more of an art than science.\cb1 \
